<h3>Intro</h3>

<p>AIMO3 is a reasoning-heavy benchmark where performance depends less on raw model size and more on <strong>how you drive the model</strong>.</p>

<p>Key idea:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Don’t trust a single generation — <strong>sample, verify, and aggregate</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>We build a solver that:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Generates multiple reasoning paths</li>
  <li>Extracts candidate answers</li>
  <li>Applies filtering and normalization</li>
  <li>Uses <strong>majority voting or scoring</strong></li>
  <li>Optionally re-prompts for refinement</li>
</ol>

<hr />

<h3>Core Strategy</h3>

<p><strong>Pipeline overview:</strong></p>

<div class="language-text highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>Prompt → Multi-sample generation → Parse answers → Filter → Vote → Final answer
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>The core philosophy is simple: treat the model as a probabilistic reasoner, not a deterministic oracle. One sample can be brilliant or brittle. Multiple independently sampled solutions, combined with strong answer extraction, are much more reliable.</p>

<hr />

<h3>Example 1 — Basic Sampling Loop</h3>

<div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">generate_solutions</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">model</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">tokenizer</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">prompt</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n_samples</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">max_tokens</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">512</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">inputs</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">tokenizer</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prompt</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">return_tensors</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s">"pt"</span><span class="p">).</span><span class="n">to</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s">"cuda"</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="n">outputs</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">generate</span><span class="p">(</span>
        <span class="o">**</span><span class="n">inputs</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="n">do_sample</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="bp">True</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="n">temperature</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.7</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="n">top_p</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.95</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="n">max_new_tokens</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">max_tokens</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="n">num_return_sequences</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">n_samples</span>
    <span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">tokenizer</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">batch_decode</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">outputs</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">skip_special_tokens</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="bp">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p><strong>Why this matters</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Diversity improves the chance of finding a correct chain of reasoning</li>
  <li>It reduces dependence on a single brittle sample</li>
  <li>It makes downstream voting and filtering possible</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h3>Example 2 — Answer Extraction</h3>

<div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">re</span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">extract_answer</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">text</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">matches</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">re</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">findall</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="sa">r</span><span class="s">'\\boxed{([^}]*)}'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">text</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">matches</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">matches</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span>

    <span class="c1"># fallback
</span>    <span class="n">numbers</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">re</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">findall</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="sa">r</span><span class="s">'-?\\d+'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">text</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">numbers</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">numbers</span> <span class="k">else</span> <span class="bp">None</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p><strong>Highlights</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Prefer <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">\boxed{}</code> answers whenever available</li>
  <li>Fall back to the last numeric value when needed</li>
  <li>Robust parsing matters as much as raw reasoning quality</li>
</ul>

<p>A surprising amount of benchmark performance can disappear due to weak extraction logic. Even strong reasoning traces are useless if the final answer parser misses the intended output.</p>

<hr />

<h3>Example 3 — Majority Voting</h3>

<div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">collections</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">Counter</span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">majority_vote</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">answers</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">filtered</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">a</span> <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">a</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">answers</span> <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">a</span> <span class="ow">is</span> <span class="ow">not</span> <span class="bp">None</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="ow">not</span> <span class="n">filtered</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="bp">None</span>

    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">Counter</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">filtered</span><span class="p">).</span><span class="n">most_common</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p><strong>Why it works</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Correct answers often cluster across samples</li>
  <li>Spurious outputs get averaged out</li>
  <li>Self-consistency is one of the highest-leverage upgrades to a simple solver</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h3>Example 4 — Full Solver Pipeline</h3>

<div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">solve_problem</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">model</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">tokenizer</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">prompt</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">outputs</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">generate_solutions</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">model</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">tokenizer</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">prompt</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n_samples</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">answers</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">extract_answer</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">o</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">o</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">outputs</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">final</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">majority_vote</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">answers</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">final</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">outputs</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">answers</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>This baseline already performs much better than a naive one-shot call, especially on competition-style problems where models may find the right logic only some fraction of the time.</p>

