<h3>Example 5 — Overcooking: What Actually Boosts Score</h3>

<p>Key tricks that made the difference:</p>

<h3 id="1-self-consistency">1. Self-consistency</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Sample <strong>8–32 outputs</strong></li>
  <li>Vote instead of trusting one generation</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="2-better-prompting">2. Better prompting</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Force a cleaner structure</li>
  <li>Ask for explicit final formatting</li>
</ul>

<div class="language-text highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>Solve step by step. Final answer in \boxed{}.
</code></pre></div></div>

<h3 id="3-filtering">3. Filtering</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Remove invalid answers</li>
  <li>Normalize integer, fraction, and modular forms</li>
  <li>Reject malformed outputs early</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="4-re-asking">4. Re-asking</h3>
<ul>
  <li>If disagreement is high, prompt again</li>
  <li>Ask the model to verify or compare top candidates</li>
  <li>Use extra compute only when confidence is low</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h3>Example 6 — Improved Prompt Template</h3>

<div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">build_prompt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">question</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="sa">f</span><span class="s">"""
You are solving a math competition problem.

Think step by step carefully.
Verify each step.

Give the final answer in </span><span class="se">\\</span><span class="s">boxed.

Problem:
</span><span class="si">{</span><span class="n">question</span><span class="si">}</span><span class="s">
"""</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Prompt structure matters more than expected. Small changes in formatting can noticeably affect both reasoning quality and answer extraction reliability.</p>

<hr />

<h3>Example 7 — Weighted Voting</h3>

<p>Instead of pure majority vote, we can use a simple heuristic score:</p>

<div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">weighted_vote</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">outputs</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">answers</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">scores</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">{}</span>

    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">out</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ans</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">zip</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">outputs</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">answers</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">ans</span> <span class="ow">is</span> <span class="bp">None</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="k">continue</span>

        <span class="n">score</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">out</span><span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># simple proxy: longer reasoning
</span>        <span class="n">scores</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">ans</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">scores</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">get</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ans</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">score</span>

    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="nb">max</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">scores</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">key</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">scores</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">get</span><span class="p">)</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>This is only a toy example, but the general idea is useful: not all candidate solutions should count equally. Some can be ranked by reasoning length, structure, confidence cues, or external verification signals.</p>

<hr />

<h3>Observations</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Majority voting alone provides large gains</li>
  <li>Prompt format matters more than expected</li>
  <li>Extraction bugs can silently destroy performance</li>
  <li>More samples do not always help indefinitely</li>
  <li>Verification is useful, but only if it is cheap and targeted</li>
</ul>

<p>In practice, the best solver is often not the most complicated one. It is the one with the cleanest end-to-end loop: generate, parse, normalize, aggregate, and only then escalate to verification if needed.</p>

<hr />

<h3>What Didn’t Help Much</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Overly complex verification chains</li>
  <li>Too many re-prompts relative to the accuracy gain</li>
  <li>Greedy decoding, which reduces useful diversity</li>
  <li>Fancy logic that added latency but not better consensus</li>
</ul>

<p>The main lesson is that many apparent improvements are not worth the compute unless they increase either answer diversity or confidence calibration.</p>

<hr />

<h3>Takeaways</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Treat LLMs like <strong>probabilistic solvers</strong>, not deterministic systems</li>
  <li>Always:
    <ul>
      <li>sample</li>
      <li>parse</li>
      <li>normalize</li>
      <li>aggregate</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>The orchestration layer often matters more than the base model</li>
  <li>Good solver design turns raw reasoning ability into usable benchmark performance</li>
</ul>

